info:
Send a series of commands to the
[Hue Bridge API V2](https://developers.meethue.com/develop/hue-api-v2/).
The commands are created from the value of the `${COMMANDS}` subflow
configuration variable.

In particular, each element of `${COMMANDS}` must contain `topic`,
`payload`, `method` and `target` members. For example, if an instance
of this subflow is configured with `${COMMANDS}` set to:

```
[
    {
        "topic": "resource/grouped_light/bad8480b-b404-42d1-a9e7-a4a69f400971",
        "payload": {
            "on": {
                "on": false
            }
        },
        "method": "PUT",
        "target": "send to ground floor hue"
    },
    {
        "topic": "resource/scene/5d507fb6-89f6-459a-b327-0fffd0c6dc48",
        "payload": {
            "recall": {
                "action": "active"
            }
        },
        "method": "PUT",
        "target": "send to ground floor hue"
    },
    {
        "topic": "resource/scene/48c39b9f-1599-4a5c-b7f6-bad6cad4029a",
        "payload": {
            "recall": {
                "action": "active"
            }
        },
        "method": "PUT",
        "target": "send to ground floor hue"
    }
]
```

that instance will send messages to turn off the Hue `grouped_light`
resource whose id is `bad8480b-b404-42d1-a9e7-a4a69f400971` and
activate the scenes whose id's are `5d507fb6-89f6-459a-b327-0fffd0c6dc48`
and `48c39b9f-1599-4a5c-b7f6-bad6cad4029a`. It does so by invoking a
`link call` node with `msg.target` set to `"send to ground floor hue"`.

**Note:** This subflow is theoretically unnecessary since one could,
in principle, define any desired lighting state as an individual scene
belonging to a particular room or zone using the Hue mobile app. In that
case, each instance of this subflow would correspond to a single command
to activate a particular such scene. This subflow exists, in part, as a
work-around for well-known limitations in the Hue bridge in regards to
the number of devices per room or zone. In addition, this subflow
allows for setting the state of combinations of lighting devices without
cluttering up the view presented to users of the Hue app with lots of
zones and scenes which would exist solely for the purposes of these
Node-RED flows but which would rarely, if ever, make sense to activate
manually. Finally, it also provides a bit of future-proofing for
changes in the Hue API since Philips sometimes exposes new features in
the bridge API before they can be accessed directly in the mobile app.

